Big happening tonight, we're likely to find out if Damar is officially brain dead. I took a few premed classes for a minor in epidemiology as well as lost a close friend after a 2 day induced coma a few years back, and to my knowledge:

There are 3 major time points to watch for with induced coma during respiratory failure: 12h, 24h, and 48h. That's when they test to see if you can breathe (with assistance) without being sedated. A nurse monitors you constantly, and you have to go 48hr consecutively without another respiratory failure. If you can't, they put you back under within 5 minutes. Hamlin obviously failed the 12h and 24h tests, so they will try again in a few hours. If he's still sedated after 48 hours, then his chances of safely regaining consciousness are miniscule and the doctors will begin asking the parents when they're ready to pull the plug.

Him being prone probably means that weening down to 50% oxygen isn't working. It means every time they try to wake him up, his capillaries are bursting and his lungs are filling up with blood due to labored and irregular breathing. This also likely happening within minutes or even seconds of IV removal, because otherwise it would be major good news.

TLDR we have about 4 hours until we find out if he has any chance whatsoever of breathing again.

>muh press conference
There's a simple explanation for such a long delay in official medical communication. Majority of such cases undergo a strict cooling protocol. Target temp is reached quickly but lasts 24h. while he's heavily sedated and chemically paralyzed. After 24h the rewarming process takes a little less than 24h but still sedated and paralyzed. Once he's rewarmed they monitor everything but gradually taper off paralysis but he may still remain sedated. From then on anything can happen including brain edema or bleeds seizures and other serious complications. You have to wait up to 72 h after he's rewarmed to be more certain ultimate recovery of brain function.
So no hospital will issue a formal conference until they go through all the steps because things can change unexpectedly.

>>128053763
He actually requires much less. Weaning means that they made one or more unsuccessful extubation (i.e. decreasing to 21% latent air oxygen) attempt(s) after his pulse stabilized, mostly likely on Tuesday afternoon and evening. Weaning is correlated with a higher mortality rate compared to successful extubation because it means that he's still experiencing respiratory failure. 100% oxygen saturation is much higher than a person needs, but so is 50%. There seems to be this misconception floating around that "50% saturation intubation" is the same as "doing half the breathing on his own," which is not the case. He is still completely dependent on intubation to get oxygen at all (because he is sedated) and weaning in no way means that he won't experience more pulmonary hemorrhaging (blood in the lungs from capillary damage) when they try to wake him up and extubate again. If he was breathing on his own, then he wouldn't require such a relatively high saturation to be tubed in while he was unconscious.

>>127991867
It depends. If it's a bigger team than you, talk them up for sure because you want them to not be motivated. If they're small you need your squad to guard against complacency but also not feel pressure (obviously this one is a little bit trickier). You need to know your squad for those. Mine right now can't handle any kind of pressure and doesn't get complacent much so I project confidence. It's basically just an extension of the team talk that the other team can hear too. It really depends on your situation and the other team's. If the other manager compliments me I usually call it condescending. If I have a good streak going against another team/manager I ALWAYS use the one that says the other team has the pressure to end it. If I have a losing streak vs them the one that sucks the Manager's dick (he's one of the best managers in the game and that's a level I've yet to reach) seems to work often enough. It doesn't like guarantee you a win but sometimes it has a noticeable effect where some CL team will play like shit against you or whatever. Usually I avoid talking about opposition players individually though unless they have a shit personality. Bottom line is you can dictate the narrative by only answering the ones you want to be the story and if you're not sure, just go fully neutral

Formula they used.

Basic Model
Dominance, 20% -- number of National Championships
Peak Strength, 20% -- winning percentage for best 50 seasons in program history
Since integration, 30% -- winning percentage over the past 50 seasons (1969-2018)
Early Modern, 20% -- winning percentage over the middle 50 seasons (1919-1968). Mostly pre-integration and included some games against non-college teams
Pre-modern, 10% -- winning percentage over the first 50 seasons (1869-1918) *mostly pre-standardization of current rules and many games against non-college teams

Adjustments
National championships below the FBS level count at 50%
National championships before the poll era (1936) count at 50%
Winning percentages when a team was not in Division I are reduced by 10%

posts.com:
For a small amount of perspective at this moment, imagine you were born in 1900. When you are 14, World War I starts and ends on your 18th birthday with 22 million people killed. Later in the year, a Spanish Flu epidemic hits the planet and runs until you are 20. Fifty million people die from it in those two years. Yes, 50 million.
When you’re 29, the Great Depression begins. Unemployment hits 25%, global GDP drops 27%. That runs until you are 33. The country nearly collapses along with the world economy.
When you turn 39, World War II starts. You aren’t even over the hill yet.
When you’re 41, the United States is fully pulled into WWII. Between your 39th and 45th birthday, 75 million people perish in the war and the Holocaust kills six million.
At 52, the Korean War starts and five million perish.
At 64 the Vietnam War begins, and it doesn’t end for many years. Four million people die in that conflict.
Approaching your 62nd birthday you have the Cuban Missile Crisis, a tipping point in the Cold War. Life on our planet, as we know it, could well have ended. Great leaders prevented that from happening.
As you turn 75, the Vietnam War finally ends.
Think of everyone on the planet born in 1900. How do you survive all of that? A kid in 1985 didn’t think their 85-year-old grandparents understood how hard school was. Yet those grandparents (and now great grandparents) survived through everything listed above.
